<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / International Company News: Nickel recovery helps Inco to
improve operating performance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Higher metals prices helped Inco, the western world's biggest nickel
producer, to report a sharp improvement in third-quarter operating
performance.
But the Toronto-based company's bottom line was dented by an accident at one
of its Manitoba mines, which forced it to cut production by 8m lbs during
the quarter, and spend USDollars 5m on repairs.
The shortfall in deliveries was made up by purchases from other producers,
on which there was little, if any, profit.
Net earnings were USDollars 2.6m, or two cents a share, down from Dollars
91.2m, or 83 cents a share, a year earlier. Last year's figure included a
Dollars 127.9m, or Dollars 1.16 a share, gain from the sale of Inco's
controlling stake in TVX Gold, a medium-sized gold producer.
Third-quarter earnings were also hurt by a Dollars 7m payout resulting from
the early redemption of a series of Swiss franc debentures.
Sales climbed to Dollars 603.2m from Dollars 468m. Operating earnings were
Dollars 47m, compared with a Dollars 13m loss. Total debt at the end of the
quarter stood at Dollars 1.01bn, down from Dollars 1.06bn last December.
Finished nickel inventories fell to 46m lbs from from 75m lbs three months
earlier. The drop was largely attributable to summer holiday shutdowns at
the Ontario and Manitoba Divisions during the third quarter.
However, the recent recovery in the nickel market has led Inco to consider
reducing next year's holidays. The company said it may shorten the summer
shutdown from four to two weeks. Discussions with trade unions are due to be
held in the first week of December.
Total nickel deliveries rose to 125m lbs from 111m lbs. Copper shipments
were 51m lbs, up from 42m lbs.
Inco also reported an improvement in its alloys business because of higher
deliveries and reduced costs.
</TEXT>
