<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / International Company News: Steel traders rekindle interest
in Ilva operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two Italian steel traders have reignited interest in the sale of the flat
steels activities of Ilva, Italy's state-owned steel manufacturer, with
their attempt to assemble an international consortium to acquire the
company.
A spokesman for Mr Bruno Bolfo and Mr Vitorio Malacalza yesterday said their
consortium could propose an offer for Ilva Laminati Piani (ILP) in the next
few days.
IRI, the Italian state holding company which owns Ilva, is trying to meet a
European Commission deadline of the end of this year for the break-up and
sale of the company. In June it agreed the sale of Ilva's special steels
business, AST, to a German-Italian consortium for L600bn (Dollars 392m), but
no firm offers have been put forward for the much larger flat steels
operation.
Industry analysts expressed doubt yesterday about the viability of a
Bolfo-Malacalza offer, but the appearance of a new potential bidder could
accelerate the sale process, just when it seemed becalmed for lack of
interest. For example, Lucchini, the private Italian steel manufacturer, is
understood to be stepping up discussions with Usinor Sacilor of France about
ILP, after Mr Bolfo approached Mr Francis Mer, Usinor's chairman, with his
plans last week.
Mr Bolfo, who used to work for the export arm of Ilva's predecessor
Finsider, and Mr Malacalza claim already to have the support from CSN, the
Brazilian steel producer, and the US securities house Smith Barney, which
they say would put together funding for a minority stake in ILP. Apart from
Usinor, they are also courting Bethlehem Steel of the US and Dofasco of
Canada. Press reports suggest an offer could be worth about Dollars 900m.
Bethlehem has expressed caution about its involvement with Mr Bolfo, who
founded Duferco, an international steel trading company, in 1977.
Lucchini has said it would offer industrial backing to ILP, if required. IRI
has also been approached by a consortium organised by the Washington-based
merchant bank G William Miller, and including local Italian entrepreneurs.
Brussels probes steel takeover plan, Page 3
</TEXT>
