<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / East Midlands to pay out Pounds 186m: Special interim
dividend of 85p is largest distribution to investors by cash-rich regional
electricity groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
East Midlands Electricity is to give Pounds 186m back to its shareholders in
a special interim dividend payment. The pay-out, which brings to nearly
Pounds 1bn the amounts returned to shareholders by privatised electricity
companies this year, drew a call from Labour for a government inquiry into
'profiteering'.
Mr Jack Cunningham, shadow trade and industry secretary, said: 'East
Midlands consumers have been forced to pay 20 per cent more for their
electricity since privatisation and the government and the regulator have
done nothing about it.'
The Nottingham-based regional distributor is to pay 85p net per share to
shareholders who owned their shares before trading started yesterday
morning. To offset the effects of this cash outlay - the largest in the
sector so far - the company will also consolidate every 25 shares into 22
new ones. East Midlands will retain the right to buy up to 10 per cent of
its shares.
The plan, which will be put to shareholders on November 18, marks a new
departure in the industry's efforts to distribute surplus cash to
shareholders.
Mr Nigel Rudd, chairman, said the payment was more fair than share buy-backs
announced by other regional electricity companies. All investors would
benefit, he said, rather than just large ones. The special dividend and the
share consolidation will also benefit employees who are either outright
shareholders or members of savings schemes which confer options to buy
shares at a set price in the future.
The dividend will carry a tax credit, which means gross funds will be able
to reclaim tax, bringing their total receipts to more than Pounds 1 a share.
East Midlands' decision was influenced by the new strategy it adopted
earlier this year of concentrating on its core business and returning
surplus cash directly to shareholders. This followed serious losses on
diversification ventures and a top level management upheaval. Mr Rudd said
yesterday that the underlying business was strong and generating good cash
flows.
East Midlands shares fell sharply as the shares immediately went ex-special
dividend, closing down 45p at 666p, although analysts said the overall
impact should be neutral. But the electricity sector as a whole gained on
hopes of pay-outs by other companies.
Attention focused particularly on Yorkshire Electricity and Southern
Electric, the only two distributors which have not so far bought back
shares. Another candidate was Eastern Electricity which completed its
buy-back early this year, before the August review by Prof. Stephen
Littlechild, the industry regulator, which set a new price formula for the
next five years.
Lex, Page 20;
Details, Page 23
</TEXT>
