<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Blair backs aims of radical proposal for welfare policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party's social justice commission yesterday sought to distance
the party from its 'tax and spend' reputation in welfare policy by setting
out a 15-year strategy for reforming the UK's welfare state.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's leader, seized on the long-awaited report of the
commission chaired by Sir Gordon Borrie to signal the party's intention to
ditch its long-standing commitments to across-the-board increases in social
benefits.
Backing many of the planks of the report prepared by the commission - an
independent group set up by the party two years ago - Mr Blair flatly
rejected the emphasis placed by the 'old left' on alleviating poverty by
raising benefit levels across the board.
Instead he insisted that Labour would craft a manifesto for a
second-generation welfare state designed to spur self-improvement rather
than increase dependency. Mr Blair's backing for integrating tax and
benefits for the elderly to concentrate resources on the poorest, and the
possible taxing of the child benefit paid to the affluent, undercut two
pledges given by Labour at the 1992 election.
Those pledges - to re-establish the link between pensions and child benefit
and average earnings - committed Labour to spending an additional Pounds
3.5bn a year on higher benefits.
The commission's report proposes to continue the government's policy of
raising the basic state pension only in line with prices. A new 'pension
guarantee' will ensure higher payments to poorer pensioners on an
income-related basis.
Speaking at the launch of the report, Mr Blair signalled that it would not
be a blueprint for Labour's manifesto. But he indicated that many of its
main proposals - on nursery education and on welfare-to-work benefits as
well as pensions and child benefits - would help form the basis of Labour's
own plans.
Sir Gordon, a former director-general of fair trading, presented the report
as a strategy of renewal without serious tax implications for middle-income
earners.
The report proposes a 'maximum tax bill' to limit to 'no more than 50 per
cent' the proportion of any individual's total income which could be paid in
income tax and national insurance contributions combined.
It also proposes a national minimum wage, projects to help lone parents find
childcare and wage subsidies to encourage employers to hire long-term
unemployed.
Reports, Page 8
Joe Rogaly, Page 18
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
