<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three cheers for Channel 4 and television's best culture commentary series,
Without Walls, which begins a new run with a programme I would have said was
impossible on today's politically correct television in Britain: Sun TV
critic Gary Bushell, who is nobody's fool but decidedly right wing, argues
in favour of Alf Garnett, the monstrous working class Tory bigot who made
Till Death Us Do Part such a huge success in the 1960s. Bushell extends the
argument to criticise the stranglehold achieved by Islington trendies over
so much of television these days (9.00). We shall need our VCRs since the
fifth episode in BBC2's odd but endearing, and wholly engrossing, drama
series, Takin' Over The Asylum, also begins at 9.00. I still think the
attitude towards mental patients is sentimental, but perhaps that was
necessary. BBC1 begins a new series of 'factual dramas', Against All Odds,
containing testimony from the real protagonists woven into the scripts.
Today's story tells how Linda McNeill went to Turkish Cyprus to snatch her
three children from her violent husband (9.30).
</TEXT>
