<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / TUC official raps profit-related pay as 'tax dodge'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Profit-related pay schemes are an unfair tax dodge for employers, a Trades
Union Congress official said yesterday.
Mr Bill Callaghan, head of the TUC's Economic and Social Affairs Department,
said that the TUC would be calling for an end to profit-related pay. 'I
don't think the rest of us should be subsidising companies in that way.'
The TUC said such schemes would cost the taxpayer about Pounds 500m this
year. Union leaders are suspicious that profit-related pay schemes approved
by the Inland Revenue, which involve payments of a tax-free bonus which is
not consolidated into incremental earnings, may be used as a method of
getting away from annual pay bargaining.
Mr Callaghan told a London conference on employee financial participation
that such schemes were no substitute for industrial democracy.
He said: 'If workers are to share some of the entrepreneurial risks of a
business then they should have the opportunity to influence strategic
decisions.'
A report on employee financial participation in companies, published by the
Confederation of British Industry, the employers' organisation, and Cable
and Wireless, the telecommunications group, showed a big growth in
profit-sharing schemes in the past four years.
The report found that almost two-thirds of nearly 300 organisations
questioned were operating some form of financial participation scheme.
Executive share options were the most popular form of schemes approved by
the Inland Revenue used by 37 per cent of the companies, while 29 per cent
operated save-as-you-earn schemes and 28 per cent used profit-related pay.
Nearly a fifth said they used such schemes to replace some existing pay and
12 per cent said they used them in place of a future pay increase.
</TEXT>
