<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Horror tax video set to terrify
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You've had the nightmare, now see the video.
The Investigators, a 20-minute film produced by accountants Pannell Kerr
Forster, may be short on action but makes up for it in chilling detail.
It tells the everyday story of a businessman running a small furniture
company, and his unsuspecting accountant.
A tip-off from an aggrieved associate leads to an Inland Revenue
investigation.
Our hero, the accountant, and his client, are called to an interview with
the inquiry branch. The businessman disastrously underestimates the
situation: 'I'm supposed to be playing golf that day.'
He ends up admitting to fraud, much to the amazement of his accountant, and
the film ends with the tax inspectors searching his home safe for further
evidence.
The video, which will be shown to chambers of commerce and other groups, is
designed to emphasise the growing need for businesspeople to have expert tax
advice.
Pannell Kerr Forster says it believes everyone has the right to the best
advice possible.
'The Investigators leaves the audience with no illusions about the Revenue's
power to gather information and their willingness when they consider it
appropriate to visit business premises and taxpayers' homes in their quest
to recover tax interest and penalties,' said the film-makers.
The video comes at a time when the Revenue has increased its investigations
work to the point where the yield was Pounds 4.7bn in 1993-94, or the
equivalent of 2.5p on the basic rate of income tax.
The government is also to consider a report by Mr Phillip Ely, former
president of the Law Society, into proposals for the powers of tax
investigators to be widened to include access to accountants' papers.
</TEXT>
