FT  25 OCT 94 / Teachers call for action on pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Compensation arrangements for those who were wrongly advised to take out
personal pensions must include reinstatement in the original occupational
scheme, the Association of Teachers and Lecturers said yesterday.
The call for reinstatement came ahead of today's report from the Securities
and Investments Board, the City's chief regulator, on compensating the
victims of poor advice.
The union estimates that full settlement of all the cases it took up where
teachers seemed to have received bad advice could cost life insurers more
than Pounds 2m for just 140 individuals. Compensation in each of the 10
cases settled so far has been between Pounds 3,800 and Pounds 30,000.
Mr Peter Smith, ATL general secretary, expressed anger that many life
companies had refused to agree compensation before publication of SIB's
guidelines. SIB intended to publish its guidelines by the end of July but
said it wanted to assess how workable its approach would be.
