<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / World Trade News: Singapore to lose TV plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Thomson Consumer Electronics (TCE), the French multinational, is closing
down its colour television manufacturing plant in Singapore and moving
operations to Bangkok and to Batam in Indonesia. Rising costs in Singapore
are believed to be the main reason for the move. Mr Didier Trutt, a general
manager of Thomson in Asia, said the TV manufacturing industry operated
under severe cost pressures. 'Expanding our manufacturing operations in
Thailand and Indonesia, while strengthening our support functions at the
regional headquarters in Singapore, makes good economic sense,' said Mr
Trutt. TCE first set up in Singapore in 1969 and has about 5,000 workers.
About 900 employees at the Singapore plant will lose their jobs.
