FT  25 OCT 94 / Jail term for Cantabria chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Juan Hormaechea, the conservative chief executive of Cantabria in
northern Spain, yesterday became the first head of a Spanish regional
government to face jail over corruption charges. After a long legal battle,
Mr Hormaechea - a controversial local populist and former mayor of the port
of Santander, capital of the Cantabria region - was sentenced by a Santander
court to six years for embezzlement linked to construction contracts he
awarded in 1991. His imprisonment was delayed, however, pending his appeal
to the supreme court in Madrid. The sentence is an embarrassment for the
opposition Partido Popular (PP). The party had backed Mr Hormaechea when he
was first elected chief minister in Cantabria's 1988 regional elections as
an independent on the PP ticket, and has since failed to persuade him to
resign. In 1992 Mr Hormaechea, who was already facing judicial
investigation, formed his own party to fight the regional elections and was
re-elected chief minister with PP support.
