<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Observer: Skin graft
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Analysts in Germany are sensing the need to develop thick skins. No sooner
had the stock market absorbed the result of last week's narrow election
victory by chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition, than a Deutsche Bank
analysts' team in Dusseldorf recommended a sell for German shares. They
suggested the government was too weak and the political climate was moving
leftwards.
This was too much for the bank's bosses in Frankfurt. They took the highly
unusual step of distancing themselves from the views of the Dusseldorf
analysts, saying they did not reflect the bank's opinions.
Down in Munich, another analyst, from Bayerische Vereinsbank, has received a
taste of corporate spleen from Computer 2000, the German computer dealer. It
took exception to a study it thought too short-term in outlook and publicly
castigated the conclusions of 'a young analyst'. What's youth got to do with
it?
</TEXT>
