<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Slim pickings in the cinema this week. Major League II provides a sedative
for stressed-out late-year audiences, while Albert Finney slogs through an
American-backed film of Terence Rattigan's The Browning Version. Though
directed by Britain's Mike Figgis, this tale of an unloved schoolmaster
becomes a wasteland of blitzed credibility with a few small fragments of
human pathos. Watch for the howlers in the cricket match, and quail at the
just-for-Yank-audiences presence of Matthew Modine as second-lead
schoolteacher.
Better to settle in with the week's new videos. Clint Eastwood's Unforgiven
is the deconstructed cowboy masterpiece that won its star-director a hatful
of Oscars. Violent but powerful. Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs is the
famous Disney animation feature - fresh as paint after 57 years - about a
girl held hostage by extremist mineworkers. And Victor Sjostrom's The
Phantom Carriage (1920) and Benjamin Christensen's Haxan (1922) are two
marvellous Scandinavian rarities - about ghosts and witches respectively -
unearthed by the sex-and-horror video label Redemption, as if to atone for
the tripe they usually turn out.
At the ICA let me fanfare a season of Korean cinema. This lasts throughout
this week and brings another revelation from the enterprise peninsula. The
Koreans already make all our TVs, teapots and tennis shoes: now they are
turning out high-style comedies and costume dramas. Look out especially for
Soponye and Mandala, both by the veteran director Im Kwon-Taek.
It is probably time for you to book for the London Film Festival. Following
hard on Halloween, this opens on November 3 with Kenneth Branagh's
Frankenstein (Robert De Niro as the monster) and then becomes the usual
heady mixture of trick-and-treat.
More about the treats in next Thursday's film column. As for the tricks,
keep a pinch of salt handy when you read the brochure's hyperbolised
write-ups. Can 200 films all be good? Floreeat festa, but caveat emptor. The
LFF, based at London's National Film Theatre, is open to all. Inquiries,
tel: 0171-928-3232.
</TEXT>
<XX>
