<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / This Week: Man with the millions - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Have you just played badminton in a hall with a leaky roof? Swum over the
weekend in a pool that could do with the boiler turned up a notch or two?
Then write to Rodney Walker, the man who needs your help in giving away
several million pounds a week to sport's good causes.
After decades of being strapped for cash, British sport will soon be awash
with the stuff, courtesy of the new national lottery, which starts next
month. According to Walker, newly appointed to the role of sport's Santa
Claus, the most conservative revenue forecasts will provide him with Pounds
100m in the first year, rising to a minimum of Pounds 250m in 1997.
This sort of money represents a four-to-fivefold increase on current
spending by the Sports Council, where Walker is both the new chairman and
new broom.
Anyone who has sat on a charity or trust and tried to give money away will
know how hard it can be. Often there are too few applicants, and the body
handing out the cash is not sufficiently well organised to go out and find
suitable recipients. Or the claimants that do step forward are pushy, noisy
and ill-deserving.
Walker is under no illusions about his task. 'Giving it away effectively and
hitting the target consistently is going to be difficult. It's an onerous
responsibility', he said from the office of the construction business he
founded in Wakefield, Yorkshire.
His previous biggest job in sport was chairing the Rugby League, a role he
came to via the boardroom of Wakefield Trinity, the local professional club.
In chatting to Walker it seemed both essential and tactless to point out
that the Sports Council has become a byword for profligate bureaucracy.
Indeed, rigorous analysis of the malaise in many British sports would
conclude that the Sports Council is part of the problem, rather than the
answer. Luckily, its new chairman is temperamentally inclined to vigorous
cutting and pruning, an approach discreetly backed by sports minister Ian
Sproat.
However, the new boss has to square a difficult circle. He cannot start
handing out big sums with the help only of a secretary and an answerphone.
His own guess is that he'll need around 100 people spread across the country
to scrutinise applications for money, which are already flooding in at a
rate that could reach 30,000 a year.
'I'm committed to reducing bureaucracy at the Sports Council, so in a sense
it's a wonderful opportunity to transfer people across to the lottery unit
and give them something worthwhile to do,' he told me.
Whitehall's guidelines for lottery proceeds stipulate that grants be made
for capital projects rather than current spending. At first glance this
seems understandable, even laudable. On reflection, however, I have huge
doubts about its wisdom.
After all, a running track or a sports hall sounds tangible and reassuring -
money well spent. But many elite sports are short of day-to-day cash. When
the British rowing crews did so well at the world championships in the US
recently, the oarsmen had to spend around Pounds 800 each on air fares to
Indianapolis, causing considerable individual hardship.
A new boat-house at Putney or another racing shell is almost the last thing
they need. Walker is sympathetic, but says that his team must accumulate
respectability and credibility with the brief they have been handed before
they can start re-writing the rules.
'As the government's confidence in the operation grows, I'm sure they'll be
able to give us more discretion,' he predicted. Initially, his biggest
concern is to ensure that organisations qualifying for large capital grants
will have enough income to run their new assets.
'I don't want to put Pounds 2m into a wonderful new facility and then find
we've been pouring money into a black hole that's got no chance of becoming
self-funding in future,' he says.
This has been a problem with some of the projects funded by the Foundation
for Sports and the Arts, the charity set up to recycle about Pounds 40m a
year from the promoters of commercial football pools.
For example, three years ago the FSA handed over Pounds 1m to a group
planning a racing yacht for the 1994 Whitbread round-the-world race. Dolphin
&amp; Youth was duly built, but was desperately strapped for operating cash as
the race progressed. Today, there is little money to maintain her, but the
terms of the gift preclude a sale.
'There have been disappointments for the FSA, but I applaud what they've
achieved,' says Walker cautiously. His own game-plan seems to be two-fold.
First, to lean towards commercially viable projects capable of creating
their own revenue base. Community swimming pools would be a classic example.
Second, to create income-producing 'endowments' that will accompany major
grants of a type that might otherwise take years to become self-supporting.
This has echoes of the National Trust. For years this most ruthlessly
efficient of British charities has refused gifts of land or houses unless
accompanied by an endowment sufficient to cover running costs. In this way
it has avoided the financial swamps and opprobrium it would have attracted
if it had accepted roof-less country mansions or neglected woodlands.
Walker's other line of thought is to encourage applications from commercial
providers of sports facilities. It may take a little swallowing for the
traditional sports bureaucracy to see quasi-public sector money going to
those who build marinas or golf courses for profit. But he does not
hesitate. He knows he has no alternative if he is to hand out that mountain
of cash 'effectively'.
'Personally I have no trouble recommending giving the money to a successful
commercial enterprise,' he says. 'I'm a great believer in rewarding success
and effort, wherever you find it.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8699 Membership Organizations, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>RES  Capital expenditures.
    PEOP  People.
</TP>
