<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI TV Editor, Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The battle of the the sexes is likely to be fought out on sofas across
Britain as Panorama (Monday, 9.30-10.10pm, BBC1) takes on the masculinist
backlash and asks why boys are so badly done by? Girls now do better than
boys at every level of education, and women are out-smarting men in the
boardroom and beating them to some of the best jobs. The reason, according
to this programme, is an inbuilt bias against men. So do boys now need
positive discrimination?
A new series of Cutting Edge (Monday, 9.00-10.00pm, C4) begins with a
wince-inducing but very watchable fly-on-the-tiled-wall documentary on
dentistry. The patients range from a toddler with a mouth full of stumps to
a woman who worries about her teeth falling out during copulation. The
programme-makers are so keen on an authentic ambience that the sound
engineers attempted to make the drill sound just like it does when it's
resonating through your cranial cavities.
The director's director de jour is Quentin Tarantino, a former video
salesman, and it shows. His films are stuffed so full of references to other
films they almost distract you from the violence. As his latest, Pulp
Fiction, opens, Omnibus (Tuesday, 10.25-11.20pm, BBC1) finds out why his
work is considered too gamey for video release, while the big-name actors he
attracts talk about his talent.
ITV's hunger for a popular drama to rival The Sweeney has cooked up
Ellington (Wednesday, 8.30-10.00pm), in which Chris Ellison plays a sports
promotor and erstwhile boxer who hasn't given up fighting: one paw is still
pushed inside a boxing glove while the other is signing deals. It's all
here: sharp suits, shooters and shady women. But our hero is too clean to be
entirely convincing.
Panel games and political satire go together like Enoch Powell and Tony
Benn, but Have I Got News For You (Friday, 10.00-10.30pm, BBC2) manages to
make the combination work. Expect more name-calling between quiz master
Angus Deayton and team captains Ian Hislop and Paul Merton, who will be
rubbing knees this season with a line-up which includes Glenda Jackson and
Teddy Taylor.
A new season of Performance begins with a revival of Dennis Potter's
prophetically-named Message For Posterity (Saturday, 9.30-11.10pm, BBC2)
written in 1967. John Neville is the prime minister forced out of office
sitting for his portrait, and Eric Porter the painter whose political
palette is restricted to the red end of the spectrum. Quintessential early
Potter with its contrast between public and private morality and a script
that is finely honed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
