<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Masters degree aimed at directors launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A masters degree in company direction has been launched by Leeds
Metropolitan University and the Institute of Directors.
The degree differs from the conventional master of business administration
degree in being aimed at people who have already made it to the boardroom
rather than those aspiring to get there.
Courses - fees for which are Pounds 13,000 - are run in a series of two-day
modules to minimise absence from the boardroom.
Research sponsored by the institute two years ago showed that 92 per cent of
company directors received no training in how to be directors. The IoD backs
a part-time diploma course run under regional franchises by several
universities - the fees are Pounds 4,000 a head. Leeds will allow diploma
holders 24 academic credits towards the 120 needed for the new masters
degree, which is being offered nationally at a cost of Pounds 9,000 per
student.
Some training and enterprise councils have said they will pay up to half the
fees for companies registered in the government's Investors in People
training programme.
Subjects include improving personal effectiveness, information strategy,
measuring business performance, managing relationships, decision-taking and
directing strategic change.
Students for the masters degree will have to carry out a project in their
own company. Instead of being assessed by traditional academic methods such
as examinations, the degree will be awarded on project results, case
studies, presentations and reports.
Mr Chris Pierce, head of the university's executive and manager development
unit, said: 'Students will have to prove there has been a change in their
company as a result of what they have done.'
</TEXT>
