<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Inquiry starts into BAe move to develop airfield
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A public inquiry opens tomorrow into what the business community in the west
of England regards as one the most important issues for the region's
economic future.
Mrs Jean Brushfield, the Department of the Environment inspector, will be
leading the inquiry into a fiercely opposed application by British Aerospace
to develop its airfield at Filton, north Bristol, into a commercial airport.
While noise within a densely populated area - especially at night - will be
the main issue at the inquiry, the outcome is crucial to the development of
a principal regional airport for the south-west, and the argument over where
such an airport should be sited.
Watching the inquiry closely will be Bristol's existing Lulsgate airport and
Cardiff-Wales airport, which would both face tough competition, and the
promoters of two grandiose international airport schemes, one on the Severn
estuary and the other near the new Severn bridge.
Local businesspeople believe Filton airport is essential. Mr Chris Curtis,
director of the south-west Confederation of British Industry, said: 'The
south-west is probably the only UK region without a decent airport. We need
one.'
'We are far from certain Lulsgate can provide what we need. To maintain our
place as a major European region we need more airline destinations and
greatly increased services. We believe Filton can provide that. It has ideal
surface communications.'
Within an hour's drive of Filton there are 3.3m people compared with 1.7m
for Lulsgate. Few dispute that the former, close to the M4 and M5 motorways
and railway, is in principle a better location than Lulsgate, which is south
of Bristol and has poor road links and no train service.
There is a drawback. In the past decade more than 4,000 houses have been
built within two miles of Filton. After heated public meetings and thousands
of protest letters, the planning authority, Northavon District Council, has
decided to oppose BAe's application. Bristol City Council, which owns
Lulsgate, is among other objectors.
BAe said its existing airfield, used for company flights run by Air Bristol
and maintenance business, costs Pounds 1.5m a year and is under-used. It
believes scheduled services would prove a 'tremendous attraction' and help
safeguard the company's adjacent manufacturing plant, where more than 5,000
people work.
The company plans a terminal handling up to 350,000 passengers a year.
Operations would be limited to 23,000 annual movements, including 20 each
night, in addition to maintenance flights. There would be no charter
flights, although there would be freight. Airlines would fly 'quiet'
aircraft such as the BAe 146 and it is claimed the noise impact would be
small.
In contrast, Northavon council estimates 1,300 houses would suffer noise
sufficient to warrant insulation, and many expect there would soon be demand
for long-haul services and larger aircraft.
Although BAe says there could be room for two Bristol airports, Lulsgate
fears its success would be undermined. It made record pre-tax profits of
Pounds 3.6m in the year to March 31 with 1.2m passengers and said business
travel is the fastest-growing sector. It is the hub for the Brymon services
run by British Airways but, if BAe wins consent, Lulsgate could be
hard-pressed to retain these.
The Department of Transport said the government's strategy was not to direct
from the centre. Instead, it was to 'facilitate the provision of airport
capacity to meet demand substantially where it arises, while minimising the
impact of airport development on the environment'.
Consultants for Avon County Council consider Lulsgate could meet likely
demand until 2005, but approval for Filton would inhibit the necessary
investment. At Lulsgate private capital is being sought to build a Pounds
14m terminal handling up to 2m passengers a year and capable of expansion to
3.5m. This would have its own environmental impact - the airport is in a
green belt.
Bristol City Council, fearful for Lulsgate's future, is sceptical of
Filton's value in determining the region's economic well-being and believes
job creation there could be offset by job losses at Lulsgate.
The south-east regional planning conference, in a report last month,
described Lulsgate as the only south-west airport performing a regional
role. 'The one major drawback is, without doubt, the transport links which
are impossible to improve without massive investment that could not be
justified in a regional context.'
In the Filton debate, it concluded, 'a fine judgment will be required
between the need for enhanced regional and local needs for airport
facilities as against the environmental implications'.
From tomorrow, and until the inquiry is due to end in mid-January, Mrs
Brushfield will need to use that judgment.
</TEXT>
