<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Board pay rises 'at 6.1%': Slowdown seen in rate of
increases for company directors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Average pay rises for company directors are running at almost three times
the rate of inflation, a report says today.
The report by Sedgwick Noble Lowndes, the pay and benefits consultants, says
the average pay increase for directors in the past 12 months was 6.1 per
cent.
The biggest pay increases, of 9.2 per cent on average, were awarded to
deputy chief executives.
Chief executives did not appear to fare as well, with their average salary
increasing 5.1 per cent from Pounds 91,779 a year to Pounds 96,484 a year.
Divisional managing directors did better, with rises of more than 8 per
cent.
The survey, following an earlier report by Bacon &amp; Woodrow which put annual
directors' pay increases at 8.5 per cent, is further evidence that executive
pay rises have been running well ahead of average earnings.
The underlying average earnings rate in August was 3.75 per cent.
The upward trend in pay increases appears to have been stemmed in the past
three months, however.
Mr Andy Christie, the company's remuneration consulting director, said: 'For
the first time in nearly five years we are seeing a fluctuation in the
market where in one quarter the salaries are marginally up and in the next
they are dipping down again.'
The report says that the average increase for all executives was 5 per cent.
It adds that the highest average pay rises, of 5.2 per cent, were to
executives based in the midlands and the north of England. The lowest
average increases were 2.7 per cent to executives in Wales and the
south-west.
The incidence of performance-related bonuses has risen this year. Almost
half of the executives surveyed were receiving bonuses for achieving
performance targets compared with just over 44 per cent at the time of the
last report in June.
The way that bonuses are being paid is changing. Mr Christie said: 'Team
working is the most popular basis for these schemes while individual
performance, seen to be a more divisive measure, is now the least favoured.'
Trends in executive benefits packages show that health screening is on the
increase, now offered by 70 per cent of companies surveyed. Paid paternity
leave is being offered by a third of the companies.
More companies are offering cash alternatives to company cars but take up
rates are less than 1 per cent at senior levels.
Sedgwick Noble Lowndes Mangement Remuneration Database. 081-666 8591.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
