<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Retreat on council shake-ups set to embarrass ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Local Government Commission will later this week reverse recommendations
to abolish six county councils, according to local authorities which have
worked with the commission.
The move would be embarrassing for the government, which has asked the
commission, chaired by Sir John Banham, to recommend single-tier unitary
authorities to replace the existing two-tier counties and districts.
However, the commission now seems certain to recommend maintaining the
status quo in Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Cumbria, Kent, Lancashire and
Oxfordshire, having originally recommended unitary authorities in all of
them.
In Bedfordshire and Buckinghamshire it is likely to favour creating three
and four unitary authorities respectively, while in Hampshire it will
recommend making Portsmouth and Southampton unitary cities, and giving an
independent authority to the New Forest. The two-tier system seems likely to
continue in the rest of the county.
In all cases this would involve altering the first preference originally
published by the commission when it announced provisional recommendations in
June.
Sir John has repeatedly said that the commission would not recommend change
without 'overwhelming' evidence of local support. These proposals would all
follow the majority preferences shown by a survey of public opinion in the
nine counties.
The cross-party Association of District Councils, which has lobbied for
unitary authorities, criticised the survey, saying it had been 'corrupted'
by aggressive publicity campaigns mounted by county councils, which
generally support the two-tier status quo.
In Bedfordshire and Buckinghamshire, where the most popular option was to
create more unitaries than first recommended, the commission has also
changed its proposals.
The commission has postponed announcements on Berkshire and Leicestershire,
on which it also published provisional proposals in June.
It appears unable to agree on how many unitaries to create in Berkshire,
while in Leicestershire there is controversy over whether Rutland should be
recreated as a unitary county.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, cannot create a new unitary
authority unless it has first been recommended by the commission.
He has asked it to reconsider recommendations for three counties so far, but
the commission has refused to change them on all occasions and it seems
unlikely to do so in future.
Formal announcements will be made on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
