<HEADLINE>
FT  24 OCT 94 / Managers 'are more confident on sales'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sales and marketing managers have become more confident in the past three
months, the Chartered Institute of Marketing says today.
One in five of those surveyed by the institute expects to beat their sales
targets this year, compared with one in 10 of those surveyed in July. A
further 47 per cent expect to match their sales targets.
However, the managers' planned rate of sales growth this year is only 6.4
per cent, down from 7.1 per cent in the previous year. Service-sector
companies are expecting faster sales growth than manufacturing companies.
The survey shows little sign of inflationary pressures in the economy.
Managers are expecting to increase prices by 1.7 per cent this year.
The institute says the survey points to an economy that remains buoyant with
subdued inflation, but with slower growth in the second half of the year
than in the first.
The Centre of Economic and Business Research interviewed 310 managers on
behalf of the institute between September 27 and October 5.
Meanwhile, the economics department of Barclays Bank says the pace of
manufacturing growth is slowing. The bank expects manufacturing output to
grow at 4 per cent in 1995, with the strongest growth coming from the
electronics sector.
Oxford Economic Forecasting predicts that the UK economy will grow at 3.4
per cent in 1995, faster than the OECD average of 3 per cent, but slower
than the world growth rate of 4 per cent.
Inflation is expected to rise to 3.2 per cent in 1995. The OECD average is
2.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
